@Alexander Liebeskind Hey Alexander! I can't believe I'm replying to the constructor of the puzzle that became the very inspiration for my debut. 

First of all, thank you so much for creating such a stellar grammagram puzzle. I've always loved phonetic sounds and wanted to implement them in puzzles, and solving your puzzle gave me the AHA! moment I needed to start constructing.

And thanks for the kind words! This is just the beginning :)

@HeathieJ 

Pssst - It's "Nessie".

Cheers.

@Cat Lady Margaret (Am I really going to try this a third time just to get a pun in ?)

The Loch Ness Mobster probably kilt somebody.

(Now I have to leave out some giant birdseed or something?)

@Behind a book 

What is so tragic about that, though, exactly? And what are the real-life benefits of teaching often-overworked, stressed out young people two hard, dead languages on top of everything else they have to deal with? 

I ask this as a professor at university, who was taught classical Latin himself at high school.

@CaptainQuahog 

I've loved those glass flowers and plants since I was little and have made periodic visits to them over the decades (and also to the mineral room - amazing).

Way back when, I heard that their family trade was literally dying out, and that all the glass work techniques that had been passed down from generation to generation that allowed them to make such realistic glass recreations were dying with them. Ah me, nothing's permanent.

